SIMPLE: profuse
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Profuse
<hw>Pro*fuse"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>profusus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>profundere</ets> to pour forth or
out; <ets>pro</ets> forward, forth + <ets>fundere</ets> to pour: cf. F.
<ets>profus</ets>. See <er>Fuse</er> to melt.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Pouring forth with fullness or exuberance; bountiful; exceedingly
liberal; giving without stint; <as>as, a <ex>profuse</ex> government;
<ex>profuse</ex> hospitality.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A green, shady bank, <qex>profuse</qex> of flowers.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Superabundant; excessive; prodigal; lavish; <as>as,
<ex>profuse</ex> expenditure</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Profuse</xex>
ornament.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Kames.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Lavish; exuberant; bountiful; prodigal;
extravagant.</syn> -- <usage><er>Profuse</er>, <er>Lavish</er>,
<er>Prodigal</er>. <xex>Profuse</xex> denotes pouring out (as money,
etc.) with great fullness or freeness; as, <xex>profuse</xex> in his
expenditures, thanks, promises, etc. <xex>Lavish</xex> is stronger,
implying unnecessary or wasteful excess; as, <xex>lavish</xex> of his
bounties, favors, praises, etc. <xex>Prodigal</xex> is stronger still,
denoting unmeasured or reckless profusion; as, <xex>prodigal</xex> of
one's strength, life, or blood, to secure some object.
<au>Dryden.</au></usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Profuse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Profuse
<hw>Pro*fuse"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To pour out; to
give or spend liberally; to lavish; to squander.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Profusely</ent>⟦br⟧
